definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of olivetolic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.

A monocarboxylic acid that is succinic acid in which the hydroxy group of one of the carboxy groups is replaced by a pyridin-3-yl group.  A byproduct of tobacco-specific N-nitrosamines generated by cytochrome P-450 which catalyzes methylnitrosaminopyridylbutanone hydroxylation, this nicotine metabolite is commonly found in the urine of smokers.
An alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of homocysteine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A bridged compound that is 1,2-campholide substituted at position 5 by an oxo group.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of any 2',3'-cyclic nucleotide.
A member of the class of benzoic acids that is salicylic acid in which the hydrogens ortho- and para- to the carboxy group are replaced by a pentyl and a hydroxy group, respectively.
Any compound which can be used to treat or alleviate the symptoms of dyskinesia.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3,5,7-trioxododecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A pyranone that is 2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogens at positions 4 and 6 are substituted by hydroxy and pentyl groups respectively.
A pyranone that is 2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogens at positions 4 and 6 are substituted by hydroxy and 2-oxoheptyl groups respectively.
A member of the class of resorcinols that is resorcinol in which the hydrogen at position 5 is replaced by a pentyl group.
A dihydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of cannabinerolic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A dihydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of cannabigerolic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of Delta(9)-tetrahydrocannabinolic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A diterpenoid that is 6a,7,8,10a-tetrahydro-6H-benzo[c]chromene substituted at position 1 by a hydroxy group, positions 6, 6 and 9 by methyl groups and at position 3 by a pentyl group. The principal psychoactive constituent of the cannabis plant, it is used for treatment of anorexia associated with AIDS as well as nausea and vomiting associated with cancer chemotherapy.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 6 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 5 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 3 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 2 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 42 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
A sialopentaosylceramide having beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)]-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the sialopentaosyl component.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 6 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 5 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 3 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 2 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 44 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
A lignan that is gamma-butyrolactone in which the 3 and 4 positions are substituted by 4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzyl groups (the 3R,4R-diastereomer).
Any compound that improves mental functions such as cognition, memory, intelligence, motivation, attention, and concentration.
Any compound used for the treatment of eye conditions or eye diseases.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion that is the conjugate base of mycophenolic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A ceramide that is the N-2-hydroxydocosanoyl derivative of eicosasphinganine.
A ceramide that is the N-docosanoyl derivative of eicosasphinganine.
A ceramide that is the N-docosanoyl derivative of 4-hydroxyeicosasphinganine.
A ceramide that is the N-(2-hydroxydocosanoyl) derivative of 4-hydroxyeicosasphinganine.
Any compound that is able to protect normal cells from the damage caused by radiation therapy.
A ceramide that is the N-tetracosanoyl derivative of eicosasphinganine.
A ceramide that is the N-(2-hydroxytetracosanoyl) derivative of eicosasphinganine.
A ceramide that is the N-tetracosanoyl derivative of 4-hydroxyeicosasphinganine.
Any compound which inhibits the postganglionic functioning of the sympathetic nervous system (SNS).
A ceramide that is the N-(2-hydroxytetracosanoyl) derivative of 4-hydroxyeicosasphinganine.
Any compound used to suppress premature labour and immature birth by suppressing uterine contractions.
A C20 dihydroceramide in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexacosanoyl.
A ceramide that is the N-(2-hydroxyhexacosanoyl) derivative of eicosasphinganine.
